            <h2>User Guide:</h2>
            <h3> 1. What's included on Ping It? </h3>
            <p></p>
            <b> Web Performance Testing </b>
            <p> Simulates concurrent tests and allows users to input different locations from across the United States.</p>
            <p></p>
            <b> Crowdsourced Database </b>
            <p>
                Offers anonymized data from all users, in addition to data from the FCC, Sucuri Load Tester, and Netflix ISP.
                Data features broadband availability and speeds for sample websites and locations from around the world.
            </p>
            <p></p>
            <b> Data Analytics </b>
            <p> Features individual user test performance analytics, including a comparison of crowd-sourced data and user data.</p>

            <h3> 2. Understanding site-specific instructions. </h3>
            <p></p>
            <b>Website performance testing</b>
            The performance testing tables take a considerable amount of time to load your  test results
            once the submit button is clicked. This is especially true if you request multiple tests
            at the same time. However, all functionality is working as intended.
            City and state criteria are optional, as they are only available for the FireFox browser option.
            If you do not enter a city/state, then the location and state is automatically set to the location
            of the IP address of your computer. In addition, the state input must be entered as a state abbreviation
            (i.e. GA, not Georgia).
            <p></p>
            <b> Crowdsourced Database </b>
            All fields are required to view the database tables unlike previously.
            For the public website information table, the results will include only the main domain of the url.
            For example, if you enter www.google.com/questions, it will pull results using the basic domain of www.google.com.
