            <h2> Additional Resources: </h2>
            <h3>How can I stay up to date with the legal fight for net neutrality?</h3>
            The New York Times provides excellent coverage about net neutrality, including commentary and archival articles.
            Visit the site by clicking <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/topic/subject/net-neutrality"> here</a>.
            <p></p>
            <h3>What other resources are available to me?</h3>
            <p></p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <b>FCC Broadband Map</b>
                    The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) provides a visualization of residential fixed broadband deployment data,
                    as per the requirements of the FCC Form 477. The information is updated by broadband providers bi-yearly, in June and December.
                    Through this resource, users can view the broadband provider services available to them, in addition to the download and
                    upload mbps speed. Users can also access area summaries and compare broadband provisions across different areas.
                    In the event that certain broadband providers begin to change their terms of service, consumers may use this information
                    to see what other broadband services are available and accessible to them.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <b> Pingdom Live Map </b>
                    Pingdom provides a free map in which users can see how many websites are currently out of operation.
                    The map shows regions in which there are significant internet outages, and includes live updates.
                    The information is provided by over 700,000 users of Pingdom across the world.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <b> The Internet Weather Map </b>
                    The Internet Weather Map is a free service that maps latency on the Internet.
                    Volunteers from around the world feed back latency on the Internet into a central database.
                    The map displays delays of over 300ms, and refreshes every 60 seconds. The map provided by the Internet Weather Map
                    would be useful if many users  (in the U.S., specifically) struggled to maintain connections due to tampering by broadband providers.
                </li>
            </ul>
